        <h2>2.2  Introduction</h2>
		<div class="icon_intro">
            <p>
			Setting goals which are relevant and achievable is central to the rehabilitation process and is now a standard component in planning the rehabilitation process. 
		</p>
            <p>Goal setting is useful for:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><span>Facilitating communication between the PwMS and the multidisciplinary rehabilitation (MDR) team<sup>28,29</sup></span></li>
			<li><span>Aiding in the decision-making process<sup>28,29</sup></span></li>
            <li><span>Creating a person-centred outcome measure for rehabilitation<sup>28,29</sup></span></li>
		</ul>
            <p>Goals provide direction for the treatment plan and set the criteria against which progress can be examined and evaluated<sup>30</sup>.</p>
            <p>The MDR team can assist in designing goals in collaboration with the PwMS; but goals should always be patient focused. At times, the MS nurse may be 
                the team member who communicates to the patient whether a goal is realistic (or not).</p>
